Title:
EDR/XDR Bypass and Detection Evasion Techniques: An Investigation of Advanced Evasion Strategies from a Red Team Perspective

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This article surveys modern EDR/XDR telemetry and enforcement mechanisms (user-mode hooks, ETW, kernel callbacks, memory integrity, cloud correlation) and why classic post-exploitation tradecraft increasingly fails.  
- It breaks down several evasion primitives—API unhooking, BOF/COFF in-memory execution, indirect/direct syscalls, ETW suppression, and kernel callback tampering—explaining how each targets a specific visibility layer.  
- The post emphasizes “layered evasion” (combining techniques like indirect syscalls + ETW patching, or in-memory execution + sleep obfuscation) rather than relying on single bypasses.  
- It introduces “time-difference/latency” attacks that exploit delays between kernel notifications and user-mode/cloud analysis to execute actions before enforcement.  
- Case-study style sections discuss practical constraints and detection differences across products (e.g., Bitdefender user-mode hook focus; CrowdStrike/SentinelOne behavioral/stack-tracing sensitivity) and highlight residual detection vectors (memory permission flips, syscall patterns, integrity checks).  
- Useful for red teams/malware developers to understand where telemetry originates and for blue teams to derive hardening and detection ideas (integrity validation, syscall/stack anomaly detection, timer/APC monitoring, HVCI/LSA protections).

Technical Focus:
- User-mode API hooking and ntdll.dll unhooking (inline/IAT hooks)
- BOF/COFF in-memory execution and custom loaders (C2 “inline-execute” model)
- Direct/indirect system calls and syscall pattern/call-stack evasion
- ETW provider telemetry suppression (EtwEventWrite patching) and logging blind spots
- Kernel callbacks (PsSetCreateProcessNotifyRoutine / thread / image load) and tampering risks
- Timing/latency exploitation (timer-based delayed execution, suspended threads)

Use Cases:
- Evaluate how a given EDR collects telemetry (hooks vs ETW vs kernel callbacks) and map likely detection points
- Design controlled red-team tradecraft tests for fileless execution and reduced process-creation artifacts (BOF workflows)
- Build detection engineering hypotheses: monitor ntdll .text integrity changes, ETW write patching, anomalous syscall density, timer/APC-based delayed execution
- Develop defensive hardening plans: enable HVCI/Credential Guard, protect driver/registry keys, correlate memory-permission transitions with network/credential access
- Create lab benchmarks comparing tool variants (standalone PE vs BOF) and measure alerting under different EDRs/policies

Keywords:
EDR, XDR, API hooking, inline hook, IAT hooking, ntdll.dll, API unhooking, BOF, COFF, Cobalt Strike, PostExpKit, in-memory execution, direct syscall, indirect syscall, ETW, EtwEventWrite, kernel callbacks, PsSetCreateProcessNotifyRoutine, stack tracing, sleep obfuscation, SetTimer, CreateRemoteThread, VirtualAllocEx, WriteProcessMemory, NtAllocateVirtualMemory, HVCI, Credential Guard, behavioral correlation, cloud telemetry